Based on a quick summary of all the variables in this dataset, there are several missing values for variables including agepft, height, weight, BMI, asthma, father_asthma, mother_asthma, wheeze, hayfever, alelrgy, educ_parent, smoke, gassstove, fev, fvc, mmef, no_24fr, and pm2_5_fr.

calculate_mode <- function(x) {
  tbl <- table(x)
  mode_value <- as.numeric(names(tbl[tbl == max(tbl)]))
  if (length(mode_value) == 0) return(NA) else return(mode_value)
}

# separte continous and categorical 
continuous_vars <- c("agepft", "height", "weight", "bmi", "fev", "fvc", "mmef", "no_24hr", "pm2_5_fr")
categorical_vars <- c("asthma", "father_asthma", "mother_asthma", "wheeze", "hayfever", "allergy", "educ_parent", "smoke", "gasstove")

# impute missing values for continuous variables  - mean for male and hispanics
chs <- chs %>%
  group_by(male, hispanic) %>%
  mutate(across(all_of(continuous_vars), ~ ifelse(is.na(.), mean(., na.rm = TRUE), .)))

# impute missing values for categorical variables - modes for male and hispanic
chs <- chs %>%
  group_by(male, hispanic) %>%
  mutate(across(all_of(categorical_vars), ~ ifelse(is.na(.), calculate_mode(.), .)))

# Ungroup the dataset - doesn't affect stuff later 
chs <- ungroup(chs)

  1. Create a new categorical variable named âobesity_levelâ using the BMI measurement (underweight BMI<14; normal BMI 14-22; overweight BMI 22-24; obese BMI>24). To make sure the variable is rightly coded, create a summary table that contains the minimum BMI, maximum BMI, and the total number of observations per category.
chs <- chs %>%
  mutate(obesity_level = case_when(
    bmi < 14 ~ "underweight",
    bmi >= 14 & bmi < 22 ~ "normal",
    bmi >= 22 & bmi <= 24 ~ "overweight",
    bmi > 24 ~ "obese",
    TRUE ~ NA_character_
  ))
bmi_table <- chs %>%
  group_by(obesity_level) %>%
  summarise(
    min_bmi = min(bmi),   
    max_bmi = max(bmi),  
    total_observations = n()             
  )
print(bmi_table)

  1. Check your expectations

A higher fev would indicate healthier lungs since they can expell more air duirng a breath. I would expect that having a gas stove (and the parciulate matter that comes from cooking with a gas stove) as well as exposure to second hand smoke would affect the lungsâ capacity to be as effective, thus resulting in lower FEV1 volume. In addition, I would also expect that a higher BMI, would also neegativly affect FEV1 as carrying more weight could affect oneâs capacity to breath as easily.

  1. Validate with an external source

A 1999 meta analysis of 17 studies foudn a mean decrease in FEV1. with second hand smoke exposure. Another study found a negative associaton betwewen BMI and FEV1, across obese, overweight, and underweight subjects. Researchers found that as BMI increase, there is also a decrease in FEV1.

  • Bhatti U, Laghari ZA, Syed BM. Effect of Body Mass Index on respiratory parameters: A cross-sectional analytical Study. Pak J Med Sci. 2019 Nov-Dec;35(6):1724-1729. doi: 10.12669/pjms.35.6.746. PMID: 31777523; PMCID: PMC6861468.
  • Office on Smoking and Health (US). The Health Consequences of Involuntary Exposure to Tobacco Smoke: A Report of the Surgeon General. Atlanta (GA): Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (US); 2006.9, Respiratory Effects in Adults from Exposure to Secondhand Smoke. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK44316/#

Based on some early graphs there apepars to be a sight negative association with pm2.5 mass and FEV, indicating that with the more PM2.5 exposure then the less forced expiratory volume in one second. This is the opposite for BMI where the higher the BMI, the greater the FEV1. However, most subjects bend to fall below 25 BMI, introducing greater variability in the relationship for those who are overweight and obese. The relationship is harder to tell with smoke and gas stove exposure as being exposed to both secondhand smoke and gas stoves, neither, or both result in around the same FEV, but with several outliers.
